Architecture plan

Project shape:
- Vite + React + TypeScript single-page app.
- Runtime code lives under `src/`, with the browser entry and top-level app composition in `src/main.tsx`.
- Static production output is generated into `dist/` by `npm run build`, which runs `tsc -b` before `vite build`.
- Existing verification surfaces are Vitest unit tests under `src/**/*.test.ts(x)` and Playwright browser tests under `e2e/`.

Module structure and file organization:
- `src/main.tsx`: app composition and React root mounting.
- `src/components/Clock.tsx`: ticking clock UI and interval lifecycle.
- `src/components/FormatToggle.tsx`: controlled hour-format switch.
- `src/hooks/useHourFormat.ts`: persisted 12h/24h preference.
- `src/lib/formatTime.ts`: pure time formatting logic shared by UI and tests.
- `vite.config.ts`: shared dev and preview host/port configuration.
- `playwright.config.ts`: browser test configuration; Issue #23 may need a production preview command path instead of the dev server for build verification.
- `README.md`: operational commands, including the static serve command required by Issue #23.

Issue dependencies:
- Remaining implementation scope is Issue #23: Production build verification.
- Issue #23 depends on Issue 3.3 per the GitHub issue. The current repository already has a Vite app, build script, preview script, unit tests, and E2E scaffolding, so #23 should focus on validating the final production artifact rather than changing app architecture.

Key design decisions:
- Treat `npm run build` as the canonical production build command.
- Verify a clean `dist/` by removing old output before building, then confirming Vite recreates the expected static assets.
- Prefer `npm run preview` for serving the built app because it uses Vite's production preview server and existing host/port configuration.
- Document the exact build-and-serve workflow in `README.md` so production verification is reproducible.
- Keep any new production-build check narrowly scoped to build output and static serving; do not duplicate unit-level clock behavior already covered by Vitest and Playwright.
